== References == {{reflist}}
[[Category:Coins]] [[Category:American awards]] [[Category:Design awards]] [[Category:Awards established in 1984]]

The '''Eadred Reliquary''' was one of the wide-ranging [[Art forgery|art forgeries]] produced by [[Shaun Greenhalgh]] and his family, of [[Bolton, Greater Manchester]].
In 1989, Shaun Greenhalgh's father, George, tried to sell to [[Manchester University]] a supposed 10th-century Anglo-Saxon silver [[reliquary]], containing a small piece of wood which he claimed was a fragment of the [[True Cross]].<ref name=codger/> He said he had found the vessel while [[metal detecting]] in a park in [[Preston, Lancashire]].
Shaun, who had crafted the object, intended it to resemble a known missing Anglo-Saxon piece, dating back to the time of [[Eadred]], the [[King of England]] from 946 to 955. The [[British Museum]] decided that the reliquary was not genuine,<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/jan/28/ukcrime.art "'The Antiques Rogue Show'"]. ''The Guardian''. 28 January 2008. [https://www.webcitation.org/6AO2660Ne?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2008/jan/28/ukcrime.art Archived] on 2 September 2012.</ref> but the Greenhalgh family managed to sell it privately for a modest £100.<ref name=codger>Wainwright, Martin (12 January 2008). [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/jan/12/ukcrime.artnews "'Artful Codger', 84, faces jail for fencing hoax art"]. ''The Guardian''. [https://www.webcitation.org/6AO1iaM3H?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2008/jan/12/ukcrime.artnews Archived] on 2 September 2012.</ref>
